The microstructure of the prepared catalysts was further detailed using TEM (Fig. 3
                        ). LDH monomer displays a flower-like structure consisting of a large number of nanosheets (Fig. 3(A)), and pure Bi12O17Cl2 is typical of two-dimensional nanosheets (Fig. 3(B)), which are consistent with the observation of SEM diagrams. Meanwhile, tiny CQDs was also observed in the TEM diagram (Fig. 3 (C)). In addition to obtaining the morphology and dimensions of the samples, TEM can also be used to gain information about the distribution of elements and images of specific areas. High-resolution TEM (HR-TEM) was applied to describe the crystal structure in detail. The results show that good contact interfaces are formed between the three components (Fig. 3 (D)), which is beneficial to charge transfer. The lattice fringes spacing of 0.26, 0.272, and 0.320 nm correspond to the (011) crystal plane of LDH [67], the (200) plane of Bi12O17Cl2 
                        [68], and the (002) plane of CQDs [69], respectively. Furthermore, energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX) was carried out to investigate the elemental composition of the C/0.3BOC/LDH composite catalyst. The EDX plot (Fig. 3(E)) of the ternary composite reveals the presence of Ni, Al, Bi, Cl, O, and C with no impurities detected. Fig. 3(F) shows the homogenous distribution of all elements in the composite catalyst in the selected region. The above observed results are consistent with XRD, demonstrating the successful preparation of Z-scheme C/BOC/LDH heterojunction.
